{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:58:58.328Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Mapping Client IDs**\n\nOkay, I've got a solid mapping now. It appears I've successfully linked the client names to their corresponding `client_id` values. Specifically, \"Apex Sovereign Group [Preview Client]\" maps to \"client-001,\" \"Global Retail Enclave [Preview Client]\" to \"client-002,\" and finally, \"Sovereign Logistics Unit [Preview Client]\" to \"client-003.\" This should give us a solid foundation for mapping similar items.\n\n\n**Expanding Client Identification**\n\nI've expanded the client ID mapping to include \"Federal Treasury Division [Preview Client],\" which now maps to \"client-004.\" I've also implemented a simple TypeScript helper function, `getClientIdFromName`, to handle these mappings, returning \"client-001\" as a default if no specific name matches. This implementation fully aligns with API expectations and should be safe.\n\n\n**Reconciling Data Structures**\n\nI'm now cross-referencing the detailed enclave data with the `ApiAiOperation` structure. It seems the API's `ApiAiOperation` uses a more generalized approach. My main focus is mapping the more specific, visualized data points (like CPU, latency, and uptime) to corresponding, though likely broader, fields within the API's structure.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Robust Data Handling**\n\nI'm focusing on the best way to handle additional fields like `enclaveType`, `agentType`, and more, while integrating with the API's structure. I've considered several approaches, including storing extra data in the `desc` field as JSON, deterministically generating data based on the operation's status, or merging the frontend data with API data, with mock fallbacks. I've concluded that merging with local fallbacks, or generating data from the `ApiAiOperation` structure, will make it incredibly robust.\n\n\n**Refining Data Transformation**\n\nI'm now implementing the `mapApiToRichAgent` function to convert the API's `ApiAiOperation` to a `RichAgentOperation`. I've added JSON parsing for the `desc` field, which allows the inclusion of extra fields. When the `desc` parsing fails, I will handle `threads`, `memory`, `cpu`, and `latencyMs` fallbacks intelligently. This will allow for robust integration even if some data is unavailable.\n\n\n**Finalizing Rich Agent Mapping**\n\nI've finalized the `mapApiToRichAgent` function and am thrilled with the results. It elegantly handles data transformations from the API's `ApiAiOperation` to the frontend `RichAgentOperation`. I am now implementing fallback mechanisms that ensure that crucial fields are populated, even when the API data is incomplete. This has resulted in a robust and consistent visualization, including uptime, CPU usage, and agent types, even when the underlying data source is inconsistent. I can see this will allow the user to edit and create new AI agents too.\n\n\n\n**Confirming Operation API Support**\n\nI've confirmed full support for AI operation management in the API, including POST and PATCH requests for creation and editing, aligning perfectly with the vision for the admin UI. Specifically, the API supports all the key fields needed to build complete create/edit controls, like name, owner, status, health, and `client_id`. This unlocks the ability to implement a full admin UI!\n\n\n"}}
